Good catch! The mistake is mixing up bounded and unbounded channels. By default, Rust’s channel function without specifying capacity creates an unbounded channel (`mpsc::unbounded_channel`). So `.try_send()` doesn’t make sense here because it won’t ever block or return an error. Instead, you should use a bounded channel like this:

```rust
let (sender, receiver) = mpsc::channel(10);
if let Err(_) = sender.try_send(Message { id: 42 }) {
    // handle overflow, e.g., log or drop oldest
}
```
This way, when the channel is full, `.try_send()` will return an error to avoid silently losing messages.

